article.description: Neither Derek Anderson nor Bonzi Wells  shot well from the field, but both came up big at the line in the final minute, lifting the Portland Trail Blazers to an 89-85 triumph over the Seattle SuperSonics.
article.headline: Blazers knocks Sonics out of first place
article.linkText: Balanced Blazers wear out Sonics, give Kings Pacific lead
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- It took a while, but Portland's depth finally took a toll on the SuperSonics.
Wells

The Trail Blazers used a balanced attack as 10 of their players scored, led by the 16 points from Bonzi Wells, in an 89-85 victory Thursday night over Seattle. The Blazers used a 14-1 run to close the third quarter, and then never trailed. "We always talk about all these players that we have, and tonight we benefited from having all those players,'' said Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks. "This was a back-to-back ballgame where the starters looked like they were in slow motion. We went to the bench and those guys went out and came up big.'' Rasheed Wallace added 13 points for the Blazers, who have won three straight after a 3-6 start. Gary Payton had 22 points and 14 assists for the Sonics, who fell a half-game behind Sacramento for first place in the Pacific Division. "We just got outworked,'' said Sonics coach Nate McMillan, whose team lost against a Western Conference team for the first time this season. "They brought in fresh guys and were able to wear us down.'' Payton brought Seattle within 87-85 by hitting a 3-pointer with 9.5 seconds left, but the Sonics couldn't get any closer. "We just didn't play a complete 48 minutes,'' said forward Rashard Lewis. "We started out well, but it slipped away in the third quarter when our shots weren't going down. We just didn't ever completely recover.'' The Sonics went ahead 61-51 with 5:41 left in the third, but the only point Seattle got the rest of the period was a free throw from Lewis. Blazers point guard Damon Stoudamire was benched for the second time in three games. Stoudamire, who had words with Cheeks in a loss to Houston on Nov. 12, sat out the Blazers' home win over the Clippers three nights later. He returned in Wednesday night's home game against Orlando but played just 14 minutes and went scoreless. When asked why Stoudamire did not make an appearance, Cheeks said, "No comment.'' The Sonics played well early, scoring 12 fast-break points in the first quarter. But it was the shooting of the Predrag Drobnjak that gave Seattle an early lead. He scored a season-high 18 points. Brent Barry added 14, while Lewis scored 11 on just 4-of-14 shooting. Seattle led 55-42 four minutes into the second half, but its shooting went cold and the Blazers stormed back with strong play in the paint. Led by five points apiece from Dale Davis and Ruben Patterson, the Blazers outscored the Sonics 25-13 in the period. Patterson ended the game with 10 points. He provided a lot of energy in that game-turning third quarter. Scottie Pippen, who played only 21 minutes, was happy to get some rest. "Having guys in there like Ruben is fine,'' Pippen said. "He can have the minutes.'' Seattle has lost two in a row, and opens a four-game road trip Saturday at undefeated Dallas.

Game notes
Seattle guard Kenny Anderson shot around before the game but did not play for a fifth straight night because of back spasms. The team didn't yet know if he would travel on its upcoming road trip. ... As a gesture of thanks to the Seattle fans in attendance, injured center Jerome James gave $500 cash to one fan in the stands in the second quarter of the game. ... Seattle forward Reggie Evans, who entered the game without a basket, got the start and scored his first NBA field goal at the 10:40 mark of the first quarter. ... Wallace made 3-pointer in the fourth quarter, keeping his streak of at least one in every game this season.
